text: During his campaign, Trump promised to shut down the Department of Education (ED). Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text: Following the announcement of these firings, Trump then issued an executive order directing Secretary McMahon to dismantle ED.

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text: In May, Trump released a budget proposal for Fiscal Year 2026. This budget contained a $12 billion cut in funding for ED programs. This would mean eliminating before-school, afterschool, & summer programs; student supports; and teacher trainings‚Äîamong other important programs.

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text: In March, Trump announced a plan to reduce the department‚Äôs workforce by nearly half, laying off 2,000 federal employees. Last week, the Supreme Court cleared the way for the administration to go through with these mass layoffs.

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text: Since then, 24 states & DC filed a lawsuit challenging this withholding of funds. Others, including school districts & educators, have also challenged the withholding. Lawmakers, INCLUDING Republicans, & hundreds of organizations have since demanded the release of this funding.

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text: At the beginning of July, Trump notified states that he was withholding nearly $7 billion in federal education grant funding. This funding supports a wide range of programs including English language learning services and migrant education programs.

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text: Finally, in the budget bill signed into law this month, Republicans included a provision establishing the first-ever national school voucher program. This would divert billions of dollars in funding to private schools. Funding that could otherwise be going to public schools.

text: As of this week, the administration is STILL withholding over $5 billion in this funding.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
I have many concerns about the AI Executive Order signed yesterday by President Trump.

While I understand the many promised benefits of AI, I remain committed to protecting state rights, human jobs, human lives, human rights, our environment and critical water supply.

My deep concerns are that the EO demands rapid AI expansion with little to no guardrails and breaks. It also contains the threat of withholding federal funds from states who regulate AI, which is an absolute threat to federalism and why I strongly opposed the AI state moratorium originally in the BBB.

Rushed AI expansion and data centers being built all over the country from state to state with no plan in regards to environmental and critical water supply impact has massive future implications and problems. 

I‚Äôve been in construction my entire life.

I can tell you firsthand, when you move dirt there is always an impact to the surrounding area.

When you build something that requires a HIGH water demand, it will always take water away from others - that means people, cities, businesses, and surrounding counties and states. 

Data centers are like a black holes when it comes to water requirements. They consume massive amounts of water for cooling, literally millions of gallons per day. 

If you know anything about the water wars between GA,  TN, AL, and FLA, then you know states already fight each other over water supply. Counties fight each other over water supply and sue each other over PFAS/PFOS and other impacts. 

Just wait and see how bad lawsuits will become when counties are competing for data centers, in order to get rid of county property taxes, and the unintended results is new data centers that steal the water from surrounding homes and neighboring counties and states. 

Competing with China does not mean become like China by threatening state rights, replacing human jobs on mass scale creating mass poverty, and creating potentially devastating effects on our environment and critical water supply.

This needs a careful and wise approach. The AI EO takes the opposite.

Name: Jordan, Jim

.@JudiciaryGOP has been investigating European censorship since the EU tried to silence President Trump last August.

In February, we subpoenaed tech companies for their communications with foreign censors in Europe and around the world.

Name: Jordan, Jim
text: Today, we‚Äôre releasing a report with preliminary findings about the EU‚Äôs censorship regime.

Name: Jordan, Jim
text: The EU‚Äôs censorship law, the Digital Services Act (DSA), requires platforms to censor so-called ‚Äúmisinformation‚Äù and ‚Äúhate speech,‚Äù even when the content ‚Äúis not illegal.‚Äù

Name: Jordan, Jim
text: New documents obtained by the Committee show that European regulators distort these terms to require censorship of legitimate political discourse that is neither harmful nor illegal.

Name: Jordan, Jim
text: In May, the EU hosted a DSA-focused ‚Äúworkshop‚Äù where platforms were asked to consider hypothetical ‚Äúscenarios‚Äù involving hate speech online.

Name: Jordan, Jim
text:
Unlike other EU ‚Äúworkshops‚Äù with tech, the public was NOT allowed to watch this one.

And the EU told the platforms to NOT share the ‚Äúscenarios‚Äù with the public.

What were they trying to hide? https://t.co/hcqzHRyDAJ

Name: Jordan, Jim
text: Turns out, the EU wanted to hide what it defines as ‚Äúillegal hate speech‚Äù that must be censored: tweeting ordinary political rhetoric like ‚Äúwe need to take back our country.‚Äù https://t.co/jSDFE847li

Name: Jordan, Jim
text:
Documents also show that European bureaucrats are eager to censor humor and satire.

During the workshop, EU regulators indicated that platforms should use ‚Äúcontent moderation processes‚Äù‚Äîmeaning censorship‚Äîto ‚Äúaddress the use of . . . memes.‚Äù https://t.co/nkPIKDGszQ

Name: Jordan, Jim
text: Major platforms like Facebook and YouTube enforce their terms and conditions globally, meaning that EU-mandated changes will affect what Americans can say and see online. https://t.co/nqBBRNWEob

Name: Jordan, Jim
text:
And despite what the EU says publicly, this censorship cannot be limited to Europe.

Workshop materials make clear that platforms are expected to change their terms and conditions to comply with the DSA. https://t.co/fpq4PwAzpD

Name: Jordan, Jim
text:
Internal workshop notes from one American company show that these orgs are almost uniformly pro-censorship and called for aggressive content removals.

The censorship-industrial complex sadly is still thriving in Europe. https://t.co/bhiTA2sCZg

Name: Jordan, Jim
text: Under the DSA, companies are also expected to solicit feedback on content moderation from civil society organizations‚Äîmany of which are entitled to make priority censorship requests.

Name: Jordan, Jim
text:
The DSA also empowers individual countries to make takedown requests.

Our documents show that EU countries are targeting political speech on core topics like immigration and the environment.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: So the agreement he‚Äôd want would likely be that she would plead the Fifth to any questions, particularly in Trump‚Äôs personal lawsuit against the WSJ over the paper‚Äôs disclosure of the Jeffrey Epstein birthday book.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: At a minimum he‚Äôd want her silence. He would not want her testifying about Trump adversely, and particularly not about Trump‚Äôs lewd page in the Jeffrey Epstein birthday book, which WSJ says she assembled, and which Trump just now said is a fake.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Maxwell may have some recollection of their banter about the birthday page, or even of picking it up from Trump in person, any of which would indicate Trump just now lied about that. Not good for Trump to be caught in a big fat fresh Epstein lie.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: She‚Äôd be a fool to give that up for nothing, so the deal would likely provide clemency from her 20-year prison sentence. It would look too obvious to pardon her right away, so a promise of a pardon would be better, but who would believe a Trump promise?

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Still, a witness can be forced to testify even after asserting their Fifth Amendment privilege, as long as they are given immunity from any prosecution based on what they say. Courts can provide that immunity in certain instances in the interests of justice.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: It might be better to get affirmative exculpatory stuff out of her, but once she starts talking, it‚Äôs hard to stop. Selectively pleading the Fifth can lead to waiving that privilege under the shield-not-sword doctrine. So best to stick to simple silence.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: So maybe an actual pardon or formal act of clemency, dated out some months or years, with a condition of secrecy, would be the vehicle for closing the deal. If Maxwell starts pleading the Fifth to stuff, and a pardon later magically appears, you heard it here first.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories from across our district of those whose efforts create lasting change in the lives around them. Today, we shine a light on two such individuals‚Äîmeet this week's Hometown Heroes, Kevin Travers, a special education teacher at @BristolTwpSD, and @BristolTwpPD Officer Tyler Aspell.
 
Over 20 years ago, Kevin started Drummers With Attitude with little more than a few buckets, some sticks, and an idea: to create a space where every student feels like they belong. For Kevin, drumming had been a lifeline throughout his childhood‚Äîa way to cope, to focus, and to heal. He knew just how powerful that could be, and that his students could benefit from that same outlet.
 
Since then, Drummers With Attitude has become a home for students of all abilities and backgrounds‚Äîthose with disabilities, facing behavioral challenges, athletes, performers, and everyone in between. Different stories, one beat. They learn together, perform together, and take care of each other like family.
 
One of the early members of that family was Tyler Aspell.
 
Tyler grew up in Bristol Township and joined DWA as a student at Truman High School. The program gave him a sense of belonging and confidence that carried into a life of service. He joined the U.S. Army National Guard, became a Philadelphia police officer, and now serves as a Bristol Township Police Officer.
 
Recently, with his nephew now in the program, Officer Aspell returned to perform with the group, back where it all began. For the students in DWA, he wasn‚Äôt just a police officer‚Äîhe was one of them. A familiar face, a hometown success story, and a reminder of everything they‚Äôre capable of becoming.
 
That‚Äôs the legacy Kevin has built‚Äîone that doesn‚Äôt just create percussionists but builds leaders and brighter futures.
 
In 2023, I had the honor of inviting Drummers With Attitude to perform in our nation‚Äôs capital. Watching those students from our community take the stage in Washington, D.C, was an incredibly powerful moment.
 
To Kevin, thank you for creating something so extraordinary, for building a space where our students feel valued, capable, and inspired to follow their rhythm and believe in their potential. And to Officer Aspel, thank you for your service to both country and community, and for being a role model to the next generation.
 
You are both hometown heroes.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
Today, in Tenafly, I announced new bipartisan federal legislation to help protect against Lyme disease and tick-borne illnesses.

Lyme disease affects NJ families more than most states.

We need to ensure that Jersey families know how to watch out for ticks as they enjoy the outdoors this summer.

More ‚¨áÔ∏è

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
First, I am announcing the BITE Act, to create the world‚Äôs first national response system for Lyme disease and other vector-borne illnesses.

This system will utilize new technologies, including AI, to monitor high-risk areas, and alert nearby families so that they can be better prepared.

By increasing our detection and readiness capabilities, we are biting back at ticks and the diseases they carry.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
Second, my bipartisan Tick Identification Pilot Program Act will award federal grants through the CDC for states to implement tick-identification programs.

The program works by taking a picture of the tick, noting the location and date where it was encountered, and submitting it to a federal database to track encounters.

This will give families feedback within 72 hours from an expert about what kind of tick they saw, and the best next steps to protect themselves after a bite.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
Finally, I‚Äôm announcing my bipartisan Stamp Out Lyme Disease Act, which will create a brand new postage stamp to help fund research and treatments for Lyme and other tick-borne diseases.

This bipartisan legislation aims to boost investment in R&D for Lyme disease treatment.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
The bottom line: I want children and families to enjoy the natural beauty Jersey has to offer ‚Äî all the parks, trails, and recreation ‚Äî and protect themselves from tick bites and Lyme disease.

This is not a left or right issue. This is a Jersey families issue, and we need to do more.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
Israel must take immediate action and work with all possible humanitarian aid organizations to rush critically needed food and other supplies to the people in Gaza. The level of the crisis there demands emergency action. Israel‚Äôs new arrangement on delivering aid simply is not working. Israel must take all possible steps to facilitate a surge of aid into Gaza. Additionally, the United Nations and other international aid organizations must work with Israel to resolve their differences and work together so all parties can maximize the capacity of humanitarian efforts.

It is unconscionable that Hamas continues to block a negotiated ceasefire, refusing both to surrender their illegitimate power in Gaza and to release the hostages that should never have been taken in the first place. It is also unconscionable that Hamas siphons off critically needed food and supplies intended for the people of Gaza and uses it instead to prop up their terrorist organization, while at the same time fighting their war against Israel by embedding themselves into the civilian population.

But given all of this, right now it falls to Israel to take the steps necessary to alleviate the humanitarian catastrophe facing the civilian population in Gaza. I urge President Trump and his administration to work with Israel to implement a ceasefire and dramatically increase the flow of aid into Gaza. I believe we can both continue to support Israel in their effort to defend themselves against Hamas, Iran and others in the region who continue in their efforts to attack and destroy Israel, and work immediately to relieve the suffering of the people in Gaza.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Another legend has left us.  

For those who grew up in Levittown in the ‚Äò70s and ‚Äò80s, Chuck Mangione‚Äôs "Feels So Good" was so much more than just a song. It was a "snow day" anthem on WBCB radio‚Äîone of those tracks that somehow always seemed to make everything feel a little more magical. Whether you were lying in bed on a snowy morning waiting for your school name to be called, relaxing in your living room, driving down Levittown Parkway, or hearing it echo from your neighbor‚Äôs garage, it was the soundtrack to so many special memories.

His music brought people together‚Äîacross generations, across neighborhoods‚Äîand it still does.

May he rest in peace, and know what a gift he was to us all.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
When a project has the power to reshape our region, it is critical to bring everyone to the table.

Yesterday, I hosted a roundtable with Amazon, Exelon, PECO, and our local Building Trades Unions to discuss the path forward for our new AI data center in Falls Township‚Äîone of the most transformative investments Bucks County has seen in decades.

This project will:

‚úÖ Support thousands of union construction jobs 
‚úÖ Create 1,250+ high-paying tech jobs
‚úÖ Revitalize the former U.S. Steel site
‚úÖ Expand workforce pipelines and training
‚úÖ Drive long-term economic growth

It was the kind of conversation that drives progress and shapes policy‚Äîlabor and business at the same table, having honest dialogue, and a united focus on leading in innovation and American competitiveness, powered by local labor. 

Thank you to Nicole Levine (Senior VP & COO, PECO), Marie Dixon (Senior VP, Federal Affairs, Exelon), Becky Ford, Merle Madrid, and Judd Smith from Amazon, and all our amazing local Building Trades leaders representing 15 local unions, for your insights, your partnership, and your passion, and your love of America.  I look forward to continuing our partnership together as Bucks County once again leads the way in building America‚Äôs future.

text:
On this day 35 years ago, the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) was signed into law. With overwhelming bipartisan support, our government decided that no matter your ability, you are entitled to the same protections and liberties as any other American. 

It remains to be seen whether the current administration agrees with that ethos. The steep Medicaid cuts passed in HR1 will be devastating for the disability community. Slashed funding for Medicaid will force states to cut Home and Community-Based Services (HCBS) that improve the autonomy and quality of life for many disabled Americans. These services include everything from personal care assistance and assistive technology to job coaching. States choose to fund these programs with their allotted Medicaid funding. When this funding is reduced, as we saw in 2011 and 2012, these programs are cut, and equal opportunity for America‚Äôs disabled is impacted.

In the words of the Department of Justice's website, disability rights are civil rights. I will continue to fight for the rights of people with physical and intellectual disabilities to live fulfilling lives with equality.

Name: Booker, Cory A.
text:
Witnessing the catastrophic hunger and suffering of civilians, especially children, women, the sick and elderly, in Gaza has been heartbreaking. The crisis in Gaza must be met with an immediate and drastic surge in life-saving resources, such as desperately needed food, water, and medicine‚Äìincluding therapeutic foods for those suffering from severe malnutrition. It is our collective moral duty to ensure that humanitarian relief reaches those who need it most urgently.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Yesterday, I had the solemn honor of joining fellow community members to celebrate the life of Bobby Pietrangelo‚Äîa truly remarkable young man whose courage, conviction, and selfless service touched lives around the globe. 

Bobby was an Eagle Scout, a volunteer firefighter, a musician, a Pennridge honor student, and above all, a servant to others. When a medical condition kept him from joining the U.S. Marines, he did not give up on his call to serve‚Äîhe found a new path. He traveled to Ukraine, where he spent more than two years delivering humanitarian aid, rescuing the wounded, and ultimately fighting on the front lines, where he was killed in action this past January. 

Bobby was not only a hometown hero‚Äîhe was a global defender of liberty and justice. 

His legacy reminds us that patriotism isn‚Äôt confined by borders. It‚Äôs measured by the courage to stand up for what‚Äôs right, no matter where the need is greatest. 

We will never forget Bobby, and will continue to hold his family in our hearts and prayers.

Name: McClain, Lisa C.
text:
This month, I am honored to recognize Sergeant Richard Loughran as the MI-09 Veteran of the Month. A resident of Lake Orion, Michigan, Sgt. Loughran enlisted in the United States Marine Corps after he graduated from high school at just 17 years old.¬†

After graduating from basic training as a Private First Class, Sgt. Loughran was recruited to join the Communication Intelligence Group as a Japanese Code Interpreter in the Pacific Theater during World War II.¬†

Over his three years of service with the Marine Corps from 1943 to 1946, Sgt. Loughran served on the battlefields of Tinian, Saipan, Guam, and Okinawa. He played a critical role in the Wind Talkers Initiative and the radio deception efforts that led to the pivotal American victory at the Battle of Midway.

After retiring from the Marine Corps, Sgt. Loughran earned an engineering degree and founded a successful business, Data Electronics, that expanded across five states. In his civilian life, Sgt. Loughran continued to serve his community. He helped revitalize a makeup studio and became an active volunteer with Toys for Tots and local Marine Corps veterans' groups.¬†

Today, Sgt. Loughran is not only a community leader and cherished World War II veteran, but he recently celebrated his 100th birthday surrounded by five generations of loved ones.¬†

It is an honor to represent an exceptional veteran like Sgt. Loughran. His dedication to our nation and community is valiant, and he has truly made Michigan's 9th Congressional District proud. Thank you, and congratulations, Sergeant Richard Loughran!

Name: Murray, Patty
text:
Cuong Van Huynh is a hardworking and esteemed member of the Seattle and King County community. Here‚Äôs what I know from Van and the people who love him: He works full-time at Swire Coca-Cola and also runs a beloved Banh Mi and chicken wings shop, Honey Bear, with his wife in Federal Way. Van works overtime to support his two sons, who are in college studying aerospace engineering and business. He often engages in charitable works across the community and truly embodies the American dream. 

Van came to America as a refugee from Vietnam in 1984. Van was convicted back in 2006 for attempting to purchase marijuana‚Äîsince then, he has made tremendous contributions to our community. It is beyond wrong to deport a man with an American wife and two American children for trying to purchase marijuana nearly two decades ago, a substance that has now been legalized in Washington state. 

I am joining local unions and community members in calling on the Trump administration to allow Van to remain here in America, his home, with his family. Seattle and King County are better off thanks to Van, his hard work, the family he‚Äôs raised here, and the community he‚Äôs built. I hope the entire community will join me in standing with Van. This man is a pillar of our community, and he should not be torn away from his family and his home after 40 years.

‚ÄúI am deeply concerned by reports of a worsening humanitarian crisis in Gaza. Israel and humanitarian organizations must now work together to improve delivery mechanisms and routes that ensure all aid is safely and swiftly disbursed to civilians, and not diverted to Hamas. 

‚ÄúLast week, Hamas refused a ceasefire deal that would have stopped the fighting, released hostages, and surged humanitarian aid. Today in Laredo, I joined @CityofLaredo Mayor Dr. Victor D. Trevi√±o, El Metro Transit Director Robert J. Garza, Assistant GM Monica Garcia, local riders, and reporters for a public transit ride-along celebrating the largest fleet expansion in El Metro‚Äôs history.

Thanks to the $11.8M in federal funding I secured from @USDOT‚Äôs @FTA_DOT, El Metro has modernized its fleet with new, cleaner, more accessible buses. The addition of 19 compressed natural gas buses marks a major step forward in expanding transit options and reducing emissions across Laredo. Combined with local funds, this investment is transforming public transit by improving service, cutting emissions, and making rides safer.

These new buses connect seniors, students, workers, and families to jobs, school, healthcare, and opportunity. They also reduce Laredo‚Äôs carbon footprint and help keep our streets cleaner and healthier.

As a senior member of the House Appropriations Committee, I secured this funding to ensure our community has the infrastructure it needs to thrive. Investing in green, modern transit improves quality of life, drives economic growth, and strengthens our workforce.

Thank you again to Mayor Trevi√±o, Director Garza, Assistant GM Garcia, El Metro, and all our local leaders for making Laredo more connected than ever. I‚Äôll keep fighting to deliver federal investments for Laredo and #TX28.

text: The Deputy Attorney General (DAG) runs the Department of Justice; all its elements report through him to MAGA Bondi.¬†He has plenty to do other than conducting witness interviews for two days down in Florida (where they have US Attorneys).

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Senator Durbin and I had some questions about the very unusual Blanche/Maxwell meeting.¬†Here are some of the multiple weirdnesses: üßµ

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: They haven‚Äôt even said if note-takers, stenographer or recordings memorialized what was said.¬†If there‚Äôs no record, then Blanche and his sidekick just made themselves key witnesses to what went on.¬†Usually prosecutors try to avoid that.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: If it was a pardon conversation, you might want pardon office; if investigative, FBI or other federal agent; if about her conditions of confinement, Bureau of Prisons; almost anything, local US Attorney.¬†This fits in no regular procedure.

text: The only other person they‚Äôve disclosed was in the room was a political sidekick of Blanche‚Äôs from within the Deputy Attorney General‚Äôs office (ODAG).¬†That is exceedingly rare, if not unprecedented, for Department of Justice business.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: When there is no procedural thing that this bizarre meeting comports with, it suggests that this was not actual law enforcement; that Blanche had the plane, the title and the office of his official position, but was actually running Trump‚Äôs personal political errand.

text: It‚Äôs extremely rare to meet on a law enforcement matter with a subject and her attorney but have no record kept of what went on.¬†Meetings like that tend to be pretty formal, with the case agent present to write up a 302 or a stenographer taking a transcript.

Name: Pfluger, August
text:
Great to have my fellow West Texan and good friend @RepArrington at the 21st Annual West Texas Legislative Summit.

We had a great discussion to highlight why the One Big Beautiful Bill is a huge win for Texas families and businesses. It includes critical tax provisions, unleashes American energy, secures our border, supports our farmers and ranchers, makes key investments in our military, and so much more. This consequential legislation will leave a lasting impact on our communities, and I was proud to lead on it alongside Chairman Arrington to ensure it reflects our West Texas values.

Name: Langworthy, Nicholas A.
text:
Yesterday I held a press conference to mark a major victory in the fight against the opioid epidemic: the HALT Fentanyl Act has officially been signed into law.

This bipartisan legislation gives law enforcement the tools they need to crack down on traffickers and stop the flow of deadly fentanyl into our communities. With over 70,000 fentanyl-related deaths each year, this is a crucial step in protecting families, saving lives, and restoring hope.

Thank you to everyone who joined us to stand united in this fight.
